<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>offset something • set something off</xh5><p> <i>offset something—</i>1. counterbalance smth.: More had to be shifted to the opposite side of the plane to <u>offset</u> the weight of just two passengers. 2. compensate for smth.; neutralize smth.: Grants to public post-secondary institutions should be increased to <u>offset</u> the effect of inflation.</p><p> <i>set something off—</i>1. cause smth. to explode: When they <u>set the fireworks off</u>, the guards ran out to see what was making that noise. 2. give rise to smth.; start smth. happening (especially unintentionally): Labor leaders also warned such a move could <u>set off</u> violence. 3. show smth. to advantage by providing a suitable background: This new blue dress <u>sets off</u> the color of Mary’s eyes. 4. <i>= offset something 2:</i> At least there are good restaurants to <u>set off</u> the disadvantages of the weather.</p> </entry>
